WEBVTT

00:01.643 --> 00:03.225
Thanks for coming, Mrs. Trundle.

00:03.226 --> 00:05.233
Without you, the second shrimp platter

00:05.234 --> 00:07.801
would have gone completely to waste.

00:10.572 --> 00:12.007
You know,

00:12.008 --> 00:14.676
having 50 old people say
great things about your dad

00:14.677 --> 00:17.379
is exhausting.

00:17.380 --> 00:19.323
Trying to convince them
you're not the hired help

00:19.324 --> 00:20.379
is no picnic, either.

00:21.583 --> 00:23.985
You didn't complain
when they tipped you.

00:23.986 --> 00:26.287
Money's money.

00:26.288 --> 00:28.289
That Eunice was a hoot.

00:28.290 --> 00:31.593
After we straightened out
the kink in her oxygen tube.

00:31.594 --> 00:35.196
I got asked out by your
dad's 75-year-old cousin.

00:35.197 --> 00:37.032
Of course, he kept calling me Esther

00:37.033 --> 00:39.567
and asking me what heaven was like.

00:39.568 --> 00:41.202
(laughter)

00:41.203 --> 00:43.304
We don't mean to laugh on
such a sad occasion, Oscar.

00:43.305 --> 00:44.372
OSCAR: Oh, no,

00:44.373 --> 00:45.716
he would have wanted us to laugh.

00:45.717 --> 00:46.708
You know how he was.

00:46.709 --> 00:48.743
He was the best.

00:48.744 --> 00:50.345
Yeah, I loved that man.

00:50.346 --> 00:51.646
So, how are you holding up?

00:51.647 --> 00:53.081
Pretty good.

00:53.082 --> 00:54.315
I feel lucky that we

00:54.316 --> 00:57.452
were on good terms after
we reconnected last year.

00:57.453 --> 00:58.920
You're welcome.

00:58.921 --> 01:01.189
And I made sure to call him a lot.

01:01.190 --> 01:03.591
At my insistence.

01:03.592 --> 01:05.193
And said all the things
we needed to say.

01:05.194 --> 01:07.762
Also me.

01:07.763 --> 01:08.930
Felix, keep it up

01:08.931 --> 01:11.665
and you can be the next picture.

01:13.168 --> 01:14.536
Oscar, just remember,

01:14.537 --> 01:15.904
the grieving process can be tricky

01:15.905 --> 01:17.448
and it can take longer than you think.

01:17.449 --> 01:20.817
Yeah, Tuesday mornings
are going to be rough.

01:22.010 --> 01:24.073
That's when Walter and I
had our weekly video chats.

01:24.074 --> 01:25.346
Seriously, Murph?

01:25.347 --> 01:26.481
Yeah.

01:26.482 --> 01:27.949
We got real close last year.

01:27.950 --> 01:30.785
He called it Tuesdays with Murphy.

01:30.786 --> 01:32.553
(crying)

01:35.023 --> 01:37.459
There, there, buddy.

01:37.460 --> 01:39.861
I'm sorry my dad died.

01:39.862 --> 01:43.665
Here, have a sucker.

01:43.666 --> 01:46.067
I love how you put your dad's
candy all over the place.

01:46.068 --> 01:47.535
Well, making candy was his life.

01:47.536 --> 01:49.070
He would have wanted us to enjoy it.

01:49.071 --> 01:51.134
It's like every holiday
rolled into one around here.

01:51.135 --> 01:52.173
(Teddy chuckles)

01:52.174 --> 01:54.943
Oh, and death.

01:54.944 --> 01:56.744
Oscar.

01:56.745 --> 01:59.114
Need I remind you of your
recent trip to the dentist?

01:59.115 --> 02:00.215
And what did she say, hmm?

02:00.216 --> 02:01.649
That you shouldn't be allowed

02:01.650 --> 02:03.084
in the exam room with me?

02:03.085 --> 02:05.286
No, that your tooth was infected

02:05.287 --> 02:06.588
and to avoid sweets.

02:06.589 --> 02:08.732
Luckily, I am here to make
sure you follow her orders.

02:08.733 --> 02:10.191
I believe her first order was,

02:10.192 --> 02:13.261
"Get away from his mouth, Felix,
you're not a dentist."

02:13.262 --> 02:14.392
DANI: Oscar, it's time

02:14.393 --> 02:16.046
for the video conference
with your dad's lawyer.

02:16.047 --> 02:16.854
Guys, why don't we

02:16.855 --> 02:18.488
give him some space and clean up.

02:18.489 --> 02:21.358
(cell phone buzzes)

02:21.359 --> 02:23.693
It's my wife asking when
I'm going to be home.

02:23.694 --> 02:25.662
"Gonna be a while."

02:25.663 --> 02:27.330
"Very emotional day."

02:27.331 --> 02:30.067
Ooh, I got dibs on the mini quiche!

02:30.068 --> 02:31.134
(whispering): Hey!

02:31.135 --> 02:32.602
I'm worried about Oscar.

02:32.603 --> 02:34.471
He's putting on his brave face,
but I can tell

02:34.472 --> 02:36.739
he's avoiding his pain...
both dental and mental.

02:38.008 --> 02:39.443
I think he's coping pretty well.

02:39.444 --> 02:41.378
Yeah, he's holding up
better than I would be.

02:41.379 --> 02:43.780
I cry when my phone dies.

02:43.781 --> 02:46.516
You can't see it,
but as his dearest friend,

02:46.517 --> 02:49.086
I can tell you he is
crying out for help.

02:49.087 --> 02:49.920
I don't know...

02:49.921 --> 02:52.122
OSCAR: Felix, I need you!

02:52.123 --> 02:53.557
Well, well.

02:53.558 --> 02:55.926
What can I do for you,
my fragile friend?

02:55.927 --> 02:58.761
Make the lawyer face happen.

03:00.730 --> 03:01.830
Nope.

03:03.900 --> 03:05.936
(computer program beeps)

03:05.937 --> 03:07.080
LAWYER (on computer): <i>Oscar?</i>

03:07.081 --> 03:08.780
<i>Stanley Barnes.</i>

03:10.173 --> 03:11.508
<i>Nice to meet you,</i>

03:11.509 --> 03:13.710
<i>though I'm sorry about
the circumstances.</i>

03:13.711 --> 03:14.945
<i>I loved your dad.</i>

03:14.946 --> 03:16.012
Oh, thanks.

03:16.013 --> 03:17.681
He was one of a kind.

03:17.682 --> 03:23.286
<i>So let's cut to the chase: your
father was a very wealthy man.</i>

03:23.287 --> 03:25.555
<i>Crazy, crazy wealthy.</i>

03:25.556 --> 03:28.024
What? Are you sure?

03:28.025 --> 03:30.393
<i>Yes, and he's leaving it all to you.</i>

03:30.394 --> 03:32.762
<i>All $300 million and...</i>

03:32.763 --> 03:34.498
<i>Oh, wait.</i>

03:34.499 --> 03:36.332
<i>No, wrong... wrong file.</i>

03:37.467 --> 03:40.137
<i>Ah, here we go.</i>

03:40.138 --> 03:42.472
<i>Your dad had...</i>

03:42.473 --> 03:44.473
<i>next to nothing.</i>

03:46.042 --> 03:48.378
Yeah, that's more like it.

03:48.379 --> 03:52.149
<i>He did have one last request:
that you scatter his ashes</i>

03:52.150 --> 03:55.585
<i>in the river behind
his first candy factory.</i>

03:55.586 --> 03:56.686
I remember that place.

03:56.687 --> 03:58.550
When I was a kid we used
to swim in that river.

03:58.551 --> 04:02.492
Until my eyebrows fell out
and my grades started to drop.

04:02.493 --> 04:05.127
<i>What a touching memory.</i>

04:06.496 --> 04:07.898
<i>So about the ashes...</i>

04:07.899 --> 04:09.699
<i>your dad asked that you scatter them</i>

04:09.700 --> 04:13.136
<i>with someone named Patty Dombrowski.</i>

04:13.137 --> 04:15.172
Really? His old business partner?

04:15.173 --> 04:16.505
They haven't spoken in 30 years.

04:16.507 --> 04:19.209
Ooh, mysterious.

04:19.209 --> 04:20.810
What happened?

04:20.810 --> 04:23.914
I don't know, but Patty's name
was forbidden around our house.

04:23.915 --> 04:27.249
We had to call our favorite
mints "peppermint betrayals."

04:29.085 --> 04:30.687
<i>I'll email you Patty's address.</i>

04:30.688 --> 04:33.256
<i>Again, sorry for your loss.</i>

04:33.257 --> 04:35.658
<i>But congratulations
on the $300 million.</i>

04:37.127 --> 04:39.196
<i>Oh boy, I did it again.</i>

04:39.197 --> 04:41.965
Well, guess I'll have to find
Patty and take care of this.

04:41.966 --> 04:43.133
Maybe next week.

04:43.134 --> 04:45.168
No... Oscar, Oscar, Oscar.

04:45.169 --> 04:46.469
You can't put this off.

04:46.470 --> 04:48.638
You need this closure as part
of the healing process.

04:48.639 --> 04:50.173
I have closure.

04:50.174 --> 04:52.207
I'm moving on to the candy
part of the process.

04:53.910 --> 04:55.311
Fine.

04:56.479 --> 04:58.299
I'm going to need you
to empty your pockets.

05:01.518 --> 05:03.018
And your jacket.

05:09.392 --> 05:11.294
And the candy corn in your underpants.

05:11.295 --> 05:12.328
Damn it!

